It‚Äôs increasing difficult to find words in this cesspool of misinformation and hate to capture the sustained horror of this week, but I will try to my best to bear witness to:

Forensic evidence and first hand accounts proving more than 80% of the 1400 civilians massacred in Israel were tortured to death in ways we have not seen since the Holocaust -children and parents slowly tortured and killed before each others eyes. We are the only people who have to give the international community a tour of our morgues; 

Statements shared and published by those who were silent after October 7th, but are now compelled to speak out since it‚Äôs not Jewish life and children that have to be centered. This sudden compassion for humanity has also led to overnight meme-based PhDs on the Israel/Palestine conflict . To be clear, folks who outright justify torture as resistance are not even worth crying over- the history books will come for them;

Non-Jews continuing to share fringe Jewish voices of token organizations who justify their own people‚Äôs murders for followers and ‚Äúgood Jew‚Äù gold stars;

Genocidal professors at our country‚Äôs most prestigious universities segregating Jews in their classrooms and relishing in the success of their bloodthirsty freedom fighters‚Ä¶their impressionable students following their lead. 

The hate-filled murder of 6 year old Wadea Al Fayoum that brought me to my knees. 

The unfolding of the one of the greatest blood libels in recent memory following Islamic Jihad‚Äôs bombing of Al-Ahli hospital; 

Demands for a ceasefire that do not include the release of more than 200 hostages or freeing the the people of Gaza from Hamas. 

There is just too much to grieve. 

On this Friday October 20th, 2023 ‚Äîday 14 since our world changed forever, the Jews are tired. We are worn down by layer upon layer of enduring antisemitism that is as deep and inter-generational as our trauma. 

May peace come speedily in our days. May our hostages be freed, Hamas be dismantled and a ceasefire ensue. May all peace loving parents in Israel and Gaza be able to kiss their children at night. Shabbat Shalom.

