This took some years in the making; I‚Äôm delighted that @mplusmuseum in Hong Kong has acquired 17 works from my ‚ÄúOne Day We‚Äôll Understand‚Äù project, across its multiple chapters looking at the history and memory of the anti-colonial war in Malaya. 
I'm eternally grateful to gallerist Johnson Chang of @hanarttzgallery for giving me my first solo show with this work, taking a chance on me even though he‚Äôs more used to representing blue-chip artists! It was the summer of 2019, a summer of turmoil on the streets of Hong Kong, leading astute reviewers to note the parallels within the walls of Johnson‚Äôs Pedder Street gallery and just outside, on the streets where public buses burnt ‚Äî an echoing of an aspiration for a better political future, historical and contemporary. 
@arman.lam.37 helped this at-the-time newbie physically install the whole show, and has painstakingly handled this acquisition too. Thank you Arman! 

Special thanks to curator @isabttam for creating this opportunity and shepherding it tenaciously, and to the M+ team and committee. 

I‚Äôm also grateful to @zilbermangallery for helping me craft a second solo with the project, in Berlin, in 2021, developing an important new chapter ‚ÄúInterventions‚Äù, my reinterpretations of the British colonial archival photographic  prints around this conflict which I made anew as glass plates and exhibited accompanied by texts and voices representing multiple sides, perspectives to this complex war. 
@mzilberman1 and @lottelaub were partners, supporters and enablers in making that new chapter. 

@fostgallery also showed the earlier chapters of the work as a solo booth at @artbasel Hong Kong in 2022. Thank you. 

Thank you too to colleagues and friends who believed in the work from early on, and helped me craft those early shows, including @samishan, @utemeta , @anna_lovecchio_ at @ntu_ccasingapore where I was in residence in 2021 developing some of this work, Fang-tze Hsu, @jasewee and others.

